        <p>
          The Great Chicago Fire started in or near the O'Leary barn on DeKoven Street on the evening of October 8, 1871. Fueled by drought conditions and wooden construction, it burned for two days and consumed 3.3 square miles of the city. The fire jumped the Chicago River twice. Bodies were found in wells, basements, and the lake where residents had fled for safety. The exact death toll remains unknown‚Äîofficial counts of around 300 are widely considered underestimates.
        </p>
        <p>
